name: addProp
description: Add a new property to an object.

name: allPass
description: Determines whether all predicates returns true for the input data.

methods.example:
const isDivisibleBy3 = (x: number) => x % 3 === 0
const isDivisibleBy4 = (x: number) => x % 4 === 0
const fns = [isDivisibleBy3, isDivisibleBy4]
R.allPass(12, fns) // => true
R.allPass(8, fns) // => false

const isDivisibleBy3 = (x: number) => x % 3 === 0
const isDivisibleBy4 = (x: number) => x % 4 === 0
const fns = [isDivisibleBy3, isDivisibleBy4]
R.allPass(fns)(12) // => true
R.allPass(fns)(8) // => false

name: anyPass
description: Determines whether any predicate returns true for the input data.

methods.example:
const isDivisibleBy3 = (x: number) => x % 3 === 0
const isDivisibleBy4 = (x: number) => x % 4 === 0
const fns = [isDivisibleBy3, isDivisibleBy4]
R.anyPass(8, fns) // => true
R.anyPass(11, fns) // => false

const isDivisibleBy3 = (x: number) => x % 3 === 0
const isDivisibleBy4 = (x: number) => x % 4 === 0
const fns = [isDivisibleBy3, isDivisibleBy4]
R.anyPass(fns)(8) // => true
R.anyPass(fns)(11) // => false

name: chunk
description: Split an array into groups the length of size. If array can't be split evenly, the final chunk will be the remaining elements.

name: clamp
description: Clamp the given value within the inclusive min and max bounds.

name: clone
description: Creates a deep copy of the value. Supported types: Array, Object, Number, String, Boolean, Date, RegExp. Functions are assigned by reference rather than copied.

name: compact
description: Filter out all falsey values. The values false, null, 0, "", undefined, and NaN are falsey.

name: concat
description: Combines two arrays.

name: countBy
description: Counts how many values of the collection pass the specified predicate.

name: createPipe
description: Creates a data-last pipe function. First function must be always annotated. Other functions are automatically inferred.

name: difference
description: Excludes the values from other array.

name: differenceWith
description:
Excludes the values from other array.
Elements are compared by custom comparator isEquals.

name: drop
description: Removes first n elements from the array.

args.name: n
args.description: the number of elements to skip

args.name: n
args.description: the number of elements to skip

name: dropLast
description: Removes last n elements from the array.

args.name: n
args.description: the number of elements to skip

args.name: n
args.description: the number of elements to skip

name: equals
description:
Returns true if its arguments are equivalent, false otherwise.
NOTE: Doesn't handle cyclical data structures.

methods.example:
R.equals(1, 1) //=> true
R.equals(1, '1') //=> false
R.equals([1, 2, 3], [1, 2, 3]) //=> true

R.equals(1)(1) //=> true
R.equals('1')(1) //=> false
R.equals([1, 2, 3])([1, 2, 3]) //=> true

name: filter
description: Filter the elements of an array that meet the condition specified in a callback function.

name: find
description: Returns the value of the first element in the array where predicate is true, and undefined otherwise.

name: findIndex
description: Returns the index of the first element in the array where predicate is true, and -1 otherwise.

name: findLast
description:
Returns the value of the last element in the array where predicate is true, and undefined
otherwise.

name: findLastIndex
description: Returns the index of the last element in the array where predicate is true, and -1 otherwise.

methods.example:
R.pipe(
  [1, 3, 4, 6],
  R.findLastIndex((n) => n % 2 === 1)
) // => 1
R.pipe(
  [1, 3, 4, 6],
  R.findLastIndex.indexed((n, i) => n % 2 === 1)
) // => 1

name: first
description:
Gets the first element of array.
Note: In pipe, use first() form instead of first. Otherwise, the inferred type is lost.

name: flatMap
description: Map each element of an array using a defined callback function and flatten the mapped result.

name: flatMapToObj
description: Map each element of an array into an object using a defined callback function and flatten the result.

args.name: fn
args.description: The mapping function, which should return an Array of key-value pairs, similar to Object.fromEntries

args.name: fn
args.description: The mapping function, which should return an Array of key-value pairs, similar to Object.fromEntries

name: flatten
description:
Flattens array a single level deep.
Note: In pipe, use flatten() form instead of flatten. Otherwise, the inferred type is lost.

name: flattenDeep
description:
Recursively flattens array.
Note: In pipe, use flattenDeep() form instead of flattenDeep. Otherwise, the inferred type is lost.

name: forEach
description: Iterate an array using a defined callback function. The original array is returned instead of void.

name: forEachObj
description: Iterate an object using a defined callback function. The original object is returned.

methods.example:
R.pipe(
  { a: 1 },
  R.forEachObj((val) => console.log(`${val}`))
) // "1"
R.pipe(
  { a: 1 },
  R.forEachObj.indexed((val, key) => console.log(`${key}: ${val}`))
) // "a: 1"

name: fromPairs
description:
Creates a new object from an array of tuples by pairing up first and second elements as {[key]: value}.
If a tuple is not supplied for any element in the array, the element will be ignored
If duplicate keys exist, the tuple with the greatest index in the input array will be preferred.

The strict option supports more sophisticated use-cases like those that would
result when calling the strict toPairs function.

methods.example:
R.fromPairs([
  ['a', 'b'],
  ['c', 'd'],
]) // => {a: 'b', c: 'd'} (type: Record<string, string>)
R.fromPairs.strict(['a', 1] as const) // => {a: 1} (type: {a: 1})

name: groupBy
description: Splits a collection into sets, grouped by the result of running each value through fn.

args.name: fn
args.description:
the grouping function. When `undefined` is returned the item would
be skipped and not grouped under any key.

name: identity
description: A function that always returns the param passed to it

name: indexBy
description: Converts a list of objects into an object indexing the objects by the given key.

name: intersection
description: Returns a list of elements that exist in both array.

name: intersectionWith
description:
Returns a list of intersecting values based on a custom
comparator function that compares elements of both arrays.

methods.example:
R.intersectionWith(
  [
    { id: 1, name: 'Ryan' },
    { id: 3, name: 'Emma' },
  ],
  [3, 5],
  (a, b) => a.id === b
) // => [{ id: 3, name: 'Emma' }]

R.intersectionWith(
  [3, 5],
  (a, b) => a.id === b
)([
  { id: 1, name: 'Ryan' },
  { id: 3, name: 'Emma' },
]) // => [{ id: 3, name: 'Emma' }]

name: invert
description:
Returns an object whose keys are values are swapped. If the object contains duplicate values,
subsequent values will overwrite previous values.

name: isArray
description: A function that checks if the passed parameter is an Array and narrows its type accordingly

methods.example:
R.isArray([5]) //=> true
R.isArray([]) //=> true
R.isArray('somethingElse') //=> false

name: isBoolean
description: A function that checks if the passed parameter is a boolean and narrows its type accordingly

methods.example:
R.isBoolean(true) //=> true
R.isBoolean(false) //=> true
R.isBoolean('somethingElse') //=> false

name: isDate
description: A function that checks if the passed parameter is a Date and narrows its type accordingly

name: isDefined
description:
A function that checks if the passed parameter is defined and narrows its type accordingly.
To test specifically for undefined (and not null) use the strict variant of this function.

methods.example:
R.isDefined('string') //=> true
R.isDefined(null) //=> false
R.isDefined(undefined) //=> false
R.isDefined.strict(null) //=> true
R.isDefined.strict(undefined) //=> false

name: isEmpty
description: A function that checks if the passed parameter is empty

methods.example:
R.isEmpty('') //=> true
R.isEmpty([]) //=> true
R.isEmpty({}) //=> true
R.isEmpty('test') //=> false
R.isEmpty([1, 2, 3]) //=> false
R.isEmpty({ length: 0 }) //=> false

name: isError
description: A function that checks if the passed parameter is an Error and narrows its type accordingly

name: isFunction
description: A function that checks if the passed parameter is a Function and narrows its type accordingly

name: isNil
description: A function that checks if the passed parameter is Nil (null or undefined) and narrows its type accordingly

methods.example:
R.isNil(undefined) //=> true
R.isNil(null) //=> true
R.isNil('somethingElse') //=> false

name: isNonNull
description:
A function that checks if the passed parameter is not null and narrows its type accordingly.
Notice that undefined is not null!

methods.example:
R.isNonNull('string') //=> true
R.isNonNull(null) //=> false
R.isNonNull(undefined) //=> true

name: isNot
description: A function that takes a guard function as predicate and returns a guard that negates it

name: isNumber
description: A function that checks if the passed parameter is a number and narrows its type accordingly

name: isObject
description: A function that checks if the passed parameter is of type Object and narrows its type accordingly

methods.example:
R.isObject({}) //=> true
R.isObject(Promise.resolve('something')) //=> true
R.isObject(new Date()) //=> true
R.isObject(new Error('error')) //=> true
R.isObject('somethingElse') //=> false

name: isPromise
description: A function that checks if the passed parameter is a Promise and narrows its type accordingly

methods.example:
R.isPromise(Promise.resolve(5)) //=> true
R.isPromise(Promise.reject(5)) //=> true
R.isPromise('somethingElse') //=> false

name: isString
description: A function that checks if the passed parameter is a string and narrows its type accordingly

name: isTruthy
description: A function that checks if the passed parameter is truthy and narrows its type accordingly

methods.example:
R.isTruthy('somethingElse') //=> true
R.isTruthy(null) //=> false
R.isTruthy(undefined) //=> false
R.isTruthy(false) //=> false
R.isTruthy(0) //=> false
R.isTruthy('') //=> false

name: join
description:
Joins the elements of the array by: casting them to a string and
concatenating them one to the other, with the provided glue string in between
every two elements.

When called on a tuple and with stricter item types (union of literal values,
the result is strictly typed to the tuples shape and it's item types).

methods.example:
R.join([1, 2, 3], ',') // => "1,2,3" (typed `string`)
R.join(['a', 'b', 'c'], '') // => "abc" (typed `string`)
R.join(['hello', 'world'] as const, ' ') // => "hello world" (typed `hello world`)

args.name: glue
args.description: The string to put in between every two elements

methods.example:
R.pipe([1, 2, 3], R.join(',')) // => "1,2,3" (typed `string`)
R.pipe(['a', 'b', 'c'], R.join('')) // => "abc" (typed `string`)
R.pipe(['hello', 'world'] as const, R.join(' ')) // => "hello world" (typed `hello world`)

args.name: glue
args.description: The string to put in between every two elements

name: last
description:
Gets the last element of array.
Note: In pipe, use last() form instead of last. Otherwise, the inferred type is lost.

name: length
description: Counts values of the collection or iterable.

name: map
description:
Map each element of an array using a defined callback function. If the input
array is a tuple use the strict variant to maintain it's shape.

methods.signature:
R.map(array, fn)
R.map.indexed(array, fn)
R.map.strict(array, fn)
R.map.strict.indexed(array, fn)
methods.example:
R.map([1, 2, 3], (x) => x * 2) // => [2, 4, 6], typed number[]
R.map.indexed([0, 0, 0], (x, i) => i) // => [0, 1, 2], typed number[]
R.map.strict([0, 0] as const, (x) => x + 1) // => [1, 1], typed [number, number]
R.map.strict.indexed([0, 0] as const, (x, i) => x + i) // => [0, 1], typed [number, number]

name: mapKeys
description: Maps keys of object and keeps the same values.

methods.example: R.mapKeys({ a: 1, b: 2 }, (key, value) => key + value) // => { a1: 1, b2: 2 }

name: mapToObj
description: Map each element of an array into an object using a defined callback function.

args.name: fn
args.description: The mapping function, which should return a tuple of [key, value], similar to Object.fromEntries

args.name: fn
args.description: The mapping function, which should return a tuple of [key, value], similar to Object.fromEntries

name: mapValues
description: Maps values of object and keeps the same keys.

methods.example: R.mapValues({ a: 1, b: 2 }, (value, key) => value + key) // => {a: '1a', b: '2b'}

name: maxBy
description: Returns the max element using the provided predicate.

name: meanBy
description: Returns the mean of the elements of an array using the provided predicate.

name: merge
description:
Merges two objects. The same as Object.assign.
b object will override properties of a.

name: mergeAll
description: Merges a list of objects into a single object.

name: minBy
description: Returns the min element using the provided predicate.

name: noop
description: A function that returns always undefined.

name: objOf
description: Creates an object containing a single key:value pair.

name: omit
description: Returns a partial copy of an object omitting the keys specified.

name: omitBy
description: Returns a partial copy of an object omitting the keys matching predicate.

methods.example: R.omitBy({ a: 1, b: 2, A: 3, B: 4 }, (val, key) => key.toUpperCase() === key) // => {a: 1, b: 2}
R.omitBy((val, key) => key.toUpperCase() === key)({ a: 1, b: 2, A: 3, B: 4 }) // => {a: 1, b: 2}

name: once
description: Creates a function that is restricted to invoking func once. Repeat calls to the function return the value of the first invocation.

name: partition
description: Splits a collection into two groups, the first of which contains elements the predicate type guard passes, and the second one containing the rest.

args.name: predicate
args.description: a type guard function to invoke on every item

name: pathOr
description: Gets the value at path of object. If the resolved value is undefined, the defaultValue is returned in its place.

args.name: path
args.description: the path of the property to get

args.name: path
args.description: the path of the property to get

name: pick
description: Creates an object composed of the picked object properties.

name: pickBy
description: Creates an object composed of the picked object properties.

methods.example: R.pickBy({ a: 1, b: 2, A: 3, B: 4 }, (val, key) => key.toUpperCase() === key) // => {A: 3, B: 4}
R.pickBy((val, key) => key.toUpperCase() === key)({ a: 1, b: 2, A: 3, B: 4 }) // => {A: 3, B: 4}

name: pipe
description: Perform left-to-right function composition.

name: prop
description: Gets the value of the given property.

name: purry
description:
Creates a function with data-first and data-last signatures.

purry is a dynamic function and it's not type safe. It should be wrapped by a function that have proper typings.
Refer to the example below for correct usage.

name: randomString
description: Random a non-cryptographic random string from characters a-zA-Z0-9.

args.name: length
args.description: the length of the random string

name: range
description: Returns a list of numbers from start (inclusive) to end (exclusive).

name: reduce
description: Calls the specified callback function for all the elements in an array. The return value of the callback function is the accumulated result, and is provided as an argument in the next call to the callback function.

methods.signature:
R.reduce(items, fn, initialValue)
R.reduce.indexed(items, fn, initialValue)

args.name: initialValue
args.description: the initial value to use as an accumulator value in the callback function

methods.example:
R.pipe(
  [1, 2, 3, 4, 5],
  R.reduce((acc, x) => acc + x, 100)
) // => 115
R.pipe(
  [1, 2, 3, 4, 5],
  R.reduce.indexed((acc, x, i, array) => acc + x, 100)
) // => 115

args.name: initialValue
args.description: the initial value to use as an accumulator value in the callback function

name: reject
description: Reject the elements of an array that meet the condition specified in a callback function.

name: reverse
description: Reverses array.

name: sample
description:
Returns a random subset of size sampleSize from array.

Maintains and infers most of the typing information that could be passed
along to the output. This means that when using tuples, the output will be
a tuple too, and when using literals, those literals would be preserved.

The items in the result are kept in the same order as they are in the input.
If you need to get a shuffled response you can pipe the shuffle function
after this one.

methods.example:
R.sample(['hello', 'world'], 1) // => ["hello"] // typed string[]
R.sample(['hello', 'world'] as const, 1) // => ["world"] // typed ["hello" | "world"]

args.name: sampleSize
args.description: the number of elements to take

methods.example:
R.sample(1)(['hello', 'world']) // => ["hello"] // typed string[]
R.sample(1)(['hello', 'world'] as const) // => ["world"] // typed ["hello" | "world"]

args.name: sampleSize
args.description: the number of elements to take

name: set
description: Sets the value at prop of object.

name: setPath
description: Sets the value at path of object. path can be an array or a path string.

name: shuffle
description: Shuffles the input array, returning a new array with the same elements in a random order.

name: sliceString
description:
A data-last version of String.prototype.slice so it could be used in pipes.

NOTE: You don't need this function if you are calling it directly, just use
String.prototype.slice directly. This function doesn't provide any type
improvements over the built-in types.

args.name: indexStart
args.description: The index of the first character to include in the returned substring.

args.name: indexEnd
args.description: (optional) The index of the first character to exclude from the returned substring.

name: sort
description:
Sorts an array. The comparator function should accept two values at a time and return a negative number if the first value is smaller, a positive number if it's larger, and zero if they are equal.
Sorting is based on a native sort function. It's not guaranteed to be stable.

If the input array is more complex (non-empty array, tuple, etc...) use the
strict mode to maintain it's shape.

methods.example:
R.sort([4, 2, 7, 5], (a, b) => a - b) // => [2, 4, 5, 7] typed Array<number>
R.sort.strict([4, 2] as [number, number], (a, b) => a - b) // [2, 4] typed [number, number]

R.pipe(
  [4, 2, 7, 5],
  R.sort((a, b) => a - b)
) // => [2, 4, 5, 7] typed Array<number>
R.pipe(
  [4, 2] as [number, number],
  R.sort.strict((a, b) => a - b)
) // => [2, 4] typed [number, number]

name: sortBy
description:
Sorts the list according to the supplied functions and directions.
Sorting is based on a native sort function. It's not guaranteed to be stable.

Directions are applied to functions in order and default to ascending if not specified.

If the input array is more complex (non-empty array, tuple, etc...) use the
strict mode to maintain it's shape.

methods.example:
R.pipe(
  [{ a: 1 }, { a: 3 }, { a: 7 }, { a: 2 }],
  R.sortBy((x) => x.a)
) // => [{ a: 1 }, { a: 2 }, { a: 3 }, { a: 7 }] typed Array<{a:number}>
R.pipe(
  [{ a: 1 }, { a: 3 }] as const,
  R.sortBy.strict((x) => x.a)
) // => [{ a: 1 }, { a: 3 }] typed [{a: 1 | 3}, {a: 1 | 3}]

name: sortedIndex
description:
Find the insertion position (index) of an item in an array with items sorted
in ascending order; so that splice(sortedIndex, 0, item) would result in
maintaining the array's sort-ness. The array can contain duplicates.
If the item already exists in the array the index would be of the first
occurrence of the item.

Runs in O(logN) time.

name: sortedIndexBy
description:
Find the insertion position (index) of an item in an array with items sorted
in ascending order using a value function; so that splice(sortedIndex, 0, item)
would result in maintaining the arrays sort-ness. The array can contain
duplicates.
If the item already exists in the array the index would be of the first
occurrence of the item.

Runs in O(logN) time.

args.name: valueFunction
args.description:
All comparisons would be performed on the result of
calling this function on each compared item. Preferably this function should
return a `number` or `string`. This function should be the same as the one
provided to sortBy to sort the array.

args.name: valueFunction
args.description:
All comparisons would be performed on the result of
calling this function on each compared item. Preferably this function should
return a `number` or `string`. This function should be the same as the one
provided to sortBy to sort the array.

name: sortedIndexWith
description:
Performs a binary search for the index of the item at which the predicate
stops returning true. This function assumes that the array is "sorted" in
regards to the predicate, meaning that running the predicate as a mapper on
it would result in an array [...true[], ...false[]].
This stricter requirement from the predicate provides us 2 benefits over
findIndex which does a similar thing:

  1. It would run at O(logN) time instead of O(N) time.
  2. It always returns a value (it would return data.length if the
    predicate returns true for all items).

This function is the basis for all other sortedIndex functions which search
for a specific item in a sorted array, and it could be used to perform
similar efficient searches.

args.name: predicate
args.description: A predicate which also defines the array's order

args.name: predicate
args.description: A predicate which also defines the array's order

name: sortedLastIndex
description:
Find the insertion position (index) of an item in an array with items sorted
in ascending order; so that splice(sortedIndex, 0, item) would result in
maintaining the array's sort-ness. The array can contain duplicates.
If the item already exists in the array the index would be of the last
occurrence of the item.

Runs in O(logN) time.

name: sortedLastIndexBy
description:
Find the insertion position (index) of an item in an array with items sorted
in ascending order using a value function; so that splice(sortedIndex, 0, item)
would result in maintaining the arrays sort-ness. The array can contain
duplicates.
If the item already exists in the array the index would be of the last
occurrence of the item.

Runs in O(logN) time.

args.name: valueFunction
args.description:
All comparisons would be performed on the result of
calling this function on each compared item. Preferably this function should
return a `number` or `string`. This function should be the same as the one
provided to sortBy to sort the array.

methods.example: R.pipe([{ age: 20 }, { age: 22 }], sortedLastIndexBy({ age: 21 }, prop('age'))) // => 1

args.name: valueFunction
args.description:
All comparisons would be performed on the result of
calling this function on each compared item. Preferably this function should
return a `number` or `string`. This function should be the same as the one
provided to sortBy to sort the array.

name: splitAt
description: Splits a given array at a given index.

name: splitWhen
description: Splits a given array at the first index where the given predicate returns true.

name: stringToPath
description: Converts a path string to an array of keys.

name: sumBy
description: Returns the sum of the elements of an array using the provided predicate.

name: swapIndices
description:
Swaps the positions of two elements in an array or string at the provided indices.

Negative indices are supported and would be treated as an offset from the end of the array. The resulting type thought would be less strict than when using positive indices.

If either index is out of bounds the result would be a shallow copy of the input, as-is.

args.name: data
args.description: the item to be manipulated. This can be an array, or a string.

name: swapProps
description: Swaps the positions of two properties in an object based on the provided keys.

name: take
description: Returns the first n elements of array.

args.name: n
args.description: the number of elements to take

args.name: n
args.description: the number of elements to take

name: takeWhile
description: Returns elements from the array until predicate returns false.

name: times
description:
Calls an input function n times, returning an array containing the results
of those function calls.

fn is passed one argument: The current value of n, which begins at 0
and is gradually incremented to n - 1.

args.name: count
args.description: A value between `0` and `n - 1`. Increments after each function call.

args.name: fn
args.description: The function to invoke. Passed one argument, the current value of `n`.

args.name: fn
args.description: The function to invoke. Passed one argument, the current value of `n`.

name: toPairs
description: Returns an array of key/values of the enumerable properties of an object.

methods.example:
R.toPairs({ a: 1, b: 2, c: 3 }) // => [['a', 1], ['b', 2], ['c', 3]]
R.toPairs.strict({ a: 1 } as const) // => [['a', 1]] typed Array<['a', 1]>

name: type
description: Gives a single-word string description of the (native) type of a value, returning such answers as 'Object', 'Number', 'Array', or 'Null'. Does not attempt to distinguish user Object types any further, reporting them all as 'Object'.

methods.example:
R.type({}) //=> "Object"
R.type(1) //=> "Number"
R.type(false) //=> "Boolean"
R.type('s') //=> "String"
R.type(null) //=> "Null"
R.type([]) //=> "Array"
R.type(/[A-z]/) //=> "RegExp"
R.type(() => {}) //=> "Function"
R.type(undefined) //=> "Undefined"

name: uniq
description:
Returns a new array containing only one copy of each element in the original list.
Elements are compared by reference using Set.
Note: In pipe, use uniq() form instead of uniq. Otherwise, the inferred type is lost.

name: uniqBy
description:
Returns a new array containing only one copy of each element in the original list transformed by a function.
Elements are compared by reference using Set.

name: uniqWith
description:
Returns a new array containing only one copy of each element in the original list.
Elements are compared by custom comparator isEquals.

name: values
description: Returns a new array containing the values of the array or object.

args.name: source
args.description: Either an array or an object

name: zip
description:
Creates a new list from two supplied lists by pairing up equally-positioned items.
The length of the returned list will match the shortest of the two inputs.

name: zipObj
description:
Creates a new object from two supplied lists by pairing up equally-positioned items.
Key/value pairing is truncated to the length of the shorter of the two lists

name: zipWith
description:
Creates a new list from two supplied lists by calling the supplied function
